Title:
Döppel (Doppel) — Advanced Evasive Persistent Shellcode Loader for Windows

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
Döppel is a Windows C++ proof-of-concept shellcode loader designed to be evasive, VM-aware, and persistent. It focuses on defeating common analysis and telemetry by performing multiple VM/sandbox checks, unhooking `ntdll.dll`, and patching ETW. The loader retrieves an encrypted payload over TCP (RC4), then executes a staged workflow where shellcode is XOR-decrypted “just-in-time” and injected into `explorer.exe` in chunks. It includes stealthier injection details such as setting the remote thread context into a `MEM_IMAGE`-backed region to evade injected-thread heuristics, and mentions using the “gargoyle” technique to reduce in-memory scanning exposure. Persistence is implemented in an unusual way via a debugger global flag targeting `wuauclt.exe`. Useful primarily for red teamers, malware analysts, and defenders studying modern loader tradecraft and detection opportunities.

Technical Focus:
- Anti-VM / anti-sandbox checks (mouse, hardware, activity heuristics)
- `ntdll.dll` unhooking and ETW patching
- Dynamic API resolution (Kernel32) for evasion
- Staged payload retrieval (RC4 over TCP) and C2 comms (reverse-HTTPS)
- Chunked shellcode decryption/injection into `explorer.exe` + thread context manipulation (`MEM_IMAGE`)
- “Gargoyle” in-memory evasion technique + obfuscation/packing

Use Cases:
- Build/test evasive shellcode loader tradecraft in a controlled lab
- Study ETW/`ntdll` tampering and corresponding detection strategies
- Evaluate EDR heuristics around remote thread creation and injected-thread enumeration
- Reverse engineering practice on a packed/obfuscated loader with anti-analysis gates
- Prototype alternative persistence mechanisms leveraging debugger-related flags

Keywords:
Windows, C++, shellcode loader, process injection, explorer.exe, remote thread, thread context, MEM_IMAGE, ntdll unhooking, ETW patching, anti-VM, sandbox evasion, dynamic API resolution, Kernel32.dll, RC4, XOR decryption, reverse HTTPS C2, persistence, wuauclt.exe, gargoyle technique